Public Pressure, and Postwar Justice -- tChapter 12 Rough Justice and the US Approach to War Crimes Prosecution Dachau, Guantanamo Bay, and the Nuremberg Exception -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the end of World War II, the ongoing efforts aimed at criminal prosecution, restitution, and other forms of justice in the wake of the Holocaust have constituted one of the most significant episodes in the history of human rights and international law. As such, they have attracted sustained attention from historians and legal scholars. This edited collection substantially enlarges the topical and disciplinary scope of this burgeoning field, exploring such varied subjects as literary analysis of Hannah Arendt’s work, the restitution case for Gustav Klimt’s Beethoven Frieze, and the ritualistic aspects of criminal trials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xReparations 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xReparations. 0aWar crime trialszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  acollection of essays.  acriminal prosecution.  aend of world war ii.  agustav klimts beethoven frieze.  ahannah arendts work.  ahistorians.  ahistory.  aholocaust.  ahuman rights and international law.  alegal scholars.  aliterary analysis.  arestitution case.  arestitution.  aritualistic aspects of criminal trials.1 aBazyler, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoda, Norman J. W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoda, Norman J.W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula